Add Firebase to your iOS app
Add an iOS app
1
Register app
The bundle ID must consist of letters, numbers, periods or hyphens.
2
Download config file
3
Add Firebase SDK
Instructions for CocoaPods
|
Download ZIPUnityC++

Google services use CocoaPods to install and manage dependencies. Open a terminal window and navigate to the location of the Xcode project for your app.

Create a Podfile if you don't have one:
pod init
Open your Podfile and add:
# add the Firebase pod for Google Analytics
pod 'Firebase/Analytics'
# add pods for any other desired Firebase products
# https://firebase.google.com/docs/ios/setup#available-pods
Save the file and run:
pod install

This creates an .xcworkspace file for your app. Use this file for all future development on your application.

4
Add initialization code

To connect Firebase when your app starts up, add the initialization code below to your main AppDelegate class.

import UIKit
import Firebase

@UIApplicationMain
class AppDelegate: UIResponder, UIApplicationDelegate {

  var window: UIWindow?

  func application(_ application: UIApplication,
    didFinishLaunchingWithOptions launchOptions:
      [UIApplicationLaunchOptionsKey: Any]?) -> Bool {
    FirebaseApp.configure()
    return true
  }
}
5
Next steps

You're all set!

Make sure to check out the documentation to learn how to get started with each Firebase product that you want to use in your app.

You can also explore sample Firebase apps.

Or, continue to the console to explore Firebase.

Firebase alerts · New alerts
You can find your App Store ID in your app's URL. In the example below, 123456789 is the App Store ID.

https://itunes.apple.com/us/app/yourapp/id123456789
